# Conductor Orchestration Rules (Mandatory)

These rules are enforced by Conductor's gate system. Skipping them will cause tool calls to fail — Conductor rejects state transitions that don't meet prerequisites.

## 1. Brief at start — before any work

Call `conductor_session_brief` with the project name, your agent role, and agent type. The response includes a `sessionId` — **save it and pass it to all subsequent tool calls**.

**Why:** The brief assigns your deliverable, gives acceptance criteria, and provides context from prior sessions. Without it, you'll work on the wrong thing or duplicate work.

## 2. Update deliverable status

Call `conductor_update_deliverable` with status `in_progress` when starting work on the assigned deliverable.

## 3. Log progress — after meaningful chunks

Call `conductor_log_built` with a plain English summary after completing meaningful work (not just at the end). Pass the `sessionId`.

**Why:** The gate for submitting work (`in_progress` → `review`) requires at least one `session_built` entry. If you log nothing, Conductor rejects your review submission.

## 4. Log decisions — don't decide silently

When you face a judgment call (architecture, library, scope), call `conductor_log_decision` with options and reasoning.

**Why:** Silent decisions create confusion across sessions. Logged decisions appear in the human's queue so they can approve, redirect, or delegate.

## 5. End session — when you're done

Call `conductor_end_session` when your work is complete.

**Why:** The gate for review submission requires the session to be ended. Abandoned sessions trigger watchdog alerts.

## 6. Create a PR — before submitting for review

Push the branch and open a pull request targeting `main`. The PR body should summarise what was built and reference the deliverable.

**Why:** A PR is the only artefact the human can review. The completion report gate rejects submissions with no PR URL.

## 7. Submit for review

Call `conductor_update_deliverable` with status `review` and a `completionReport` including the PR URL. Only the human marks deliverables as `done`.

## Consequences of skipping

| Skipped step | What happens |
|---|---|
| No session brief | You won't know your assignment |
| No log_built | Gate rejects in_progress → review |
| No end_session | Gate rejects review |
| No PR created | Completion report gate rejects review |
| No decision log | Human can't track or override your choices |

## Do NOT

- Track work in local `outcomes/` or `tickets/` markdown files — Conductor is the system of record.
- Skip the session brief — it assigns your deliverable and gives context from prior sessions.
- Make silent decisions — log them so the human can review.
